In updating the UPM to the 2.7.0-beta2 version of the refapp the plugins system was unable to deploy UPM.

The reason was that we had an unsatisfied dep, the com.atlassian.plugin.metadata dep. We have an explicit package import for:

{code}
com.atlassian.plugin*;version="2.6",
{code}

Looking at the Felix web console it showed that the com.atlassian.plugin.metadata package is being provided at version 1.2.0-SNAPSHOT, which is the version of UPM.

I can work around the issue by adding a package import as such:

{code}
com.atlassian.plugin.metadata;version="1.2",
{code}

but that is not really ideal. I would look into this but we are kinda snowed under with UPM bugs ATM.

As a finding from [~accountid:557057:db5e6023-d299-4618-9620-a1c17c612e9f], the getDateInstalled always return lastModified of the artifact.

{code:java}
    @Override
    public Date getDateInstalled()
    {
        long date = getPluginArtifact().toFile().lastModified();
        if (date == 0)
        {
            date = getDateLoaded().getTime();
        }
        return new Date(date);
    }
{code}
It happens in both OsgiBundlePlugin and OsgiPlugin.
The method should return correctly the installed date.

The {{com.atlassian.plugin.osgi.factory.transform.stage.HostComponentSpringStage}} which generates the {{atlassian-plugins-host-components.xml}} spring context file scan for used host components that should be imported by scanning the plugin and bundled jars.

Doing so it loads the classes to check whether if they use host components, using this code:
{code:java}
Class spr;
try
{
    spr = ClassLoaderUtils.loadClass(cls, this.getClass());
}
catch (ClassNotFoundException e)
{
    // ignore class not found as it could be from another plugin
    continue;
}

// Search methods for parameters that use host components
for (Method m : spr.getMethods())
{
    for (Class param : m.getParameterTypes())
    {
        if (allHostComponents.contains(param.getName()))
        {
            matchedHostComponents.add(param.getName());
        }
    }
}
{code}

In this case getting the method tries to load a class that is imported by said class. However this is an optional dependency and this particular class is not used at runtime (here a freemarker class).

Either the {{java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError}} should be caught or we should be provided a way to exclude some classes from being scanned. Maybe both?

