In every case, I've verified that the element in question exists, but the code doesn't do anything: the browser just sits there as if nothing happened.

I have a suspicion that this is caused by us using jQuery 1.3's new ["live" events|http://docs.jquery.com/Events/live#typefn], which means that the event handlers aren't bound to the elements themselves but to some ancestor. I'd bet that Selenium's simulated events don't propagate the same way that real browser events do, so the handlers never get called.

